%I A300566 #53 Apr 16 2026 00:53:17
%S A300566 8748,10368,342732,810000,1361367,3240000,8957952,9335088,10616832,
%T A300566 25312500,31505922,43740000,52200625,216486432,350957568
%N A300566 Numbers z such that there is a solution to x^4 + y^5 = z^6 with x, y, z >= 1.
%C A300566 All z = 4*3^(10k-3) are in the sequence for k >= 1, with x = 8*3^(15k-5) and y = 8*3^(12k-4). Similarly, any z = 2^7*3^(10k+4) is in the sequence for k >= 0, with x = 2^10*3^(15k+6) and y = 2^8*3^(12k+5).
%C A300566 Also in the sequence: 512578125 = 3^8*5^7, 1215000000 = 2^6*3^5*5^7, 1701708750 = 2*3^4*5^4*7^5, 2196150000 = 2^4*3*5^5*11^4, 2431012500 = 2^2*3^4*5^5*7^4, 4269246912 = 2^6*3^4*7^7, 4447203750 = 2*3^5*5^4*11^4, 36015000000 = 2^6*3*5^7*7^4, 48717927500 = 2^2*5^4*11^7, 75969140625 = 3^4*5^8*7^4, 91116682272 = 2^5*3^4*7^4*11^4. - _Jacques Tramu_, Apr 17 2018; updated by _Max Alekseyev_, Mar 31 2026
%C A300566 Consider a solution (x,y,z) of x^4 + y^5 = z^6. For any m, (x*m^15, y*m^12, z*m^10) is also a solution. Reciprocally, if (x/m^15, y/m^12, z/m^10) is a triple of integers for some m, then this is also a solution. We call primitive a solution for which there is no such m > 1. - _M. F. Hasler_, Apr 17 2018
%C A300566 Observation: a(n) = A054744(n+38) = A257999(n+32), at least for 1 <= n <= 2 in both cases. - _Omar E. Pol_, Apr 17 2018
%C A300566 These relations hold only for n = 1 and 2. The next larger known term 342732 = 2^2*3*13^4 shows that in general the terms don't belong to A054744 nor A257999, although the earlier comment implies that each term gives rise to infinitely many non-primitive terms in A054744. - _M. F. Hasler_, Apr 19 2018
%C A300566 When S = a^4 + b^10/4 is a square, then z = b^5/2 + sqrt(S) is a solution, with x = a*z and y = b*z. All known solutions are of this form (with rational a, b). - _M. F. Hasler_, Apr 19 2018; updated by _Max Alekseyev_, Apr 04 2026
%e A300566 a(1) = 8748 = 2^2*3^7 is in the sequence because 8748^6 = (2^3*3^8)^5 + (2^3*3^10)^4, using 2^3 + 1 = 3^2.
%e A300566 a(2) = 10368 = 2^7*3^4 corresponds to (2^8*3^5)^5 + (2^10*3^6)^4, using 3 + 1 = 2^2.
%e A300566 a(3) = 342732 = 2^2*3*13^4 is in the sequence because (2^2*3*13^4)^6 = (2^3*13^5)^5 + (2^3*5*13^6)^4, using 2^3*13 + 5^4 = 3^6.
%e A300566 a(4) = 810000 = 2^4*3^4*5^4 is in the sequence because (2^4*3^4*5^4)^6 = x^4 + y^5 with x = 2^5*3^6*5^6 and y = 2^4*3^5*5^5 (using 1 + 3*5 = 2^4).
%e A300566 a(5) = 1361367 = 3^4*7^5 corresponds to x = 3^5*7^8 and y = 2*3^4*7^6.
%e A300566 a(6) = 3240000 = 2^6*3^4*5^4 corresponds to x = 2^9*3^5*5^6 and y = 2^8*3^4*5^5.
%e A300566 a(7) = 8957952 = a(1) * 2^10.
%e A300566 a(8) = 9335088 = 2^4*3^5*7^4 corresponds to x = 2^5*3^8*7^6 and y = 2^4*3^6*7^5.
%e A300566 a(9) = 10616832 = a(2) * 2^10.
%e A300566 a(10) = 25312500 = 2^2*3^4*5^7 corresponds to x = 2^3*3^6*5^10 and y = 2^3*3^5*5^8.
%e A300566 a(11) = 31505922 = 2*3^8*7^4 is corresponds to x = 3^12*7^6 and y = 3^10*7^5.
%e A300566 a(12) = 43740000 = 2^5*3^7*5^4 corresponds to x = 2^8*3^10*5^6 and y = 2^6*3^8*5^5.
%e A300566 a(13) = 52200625 = 5^4*17^4 corresponds to x = 3*5^5*17^6 and y = 2*5^4*17^5.
%e A300566 a(14) = 216486432 = 2^5*3^4*17^4 corresponds to x = 2^9*3^5*17^6 and y = 2^6*3^4*17^5.
%e A300566 a(15) = 350957568 = a(3) * 2^10.
%o A300566 (PARI) is(z)=for(y=1,sqrtnint(-1+z=z^6,5),ispower(z-y^5,4)&&return(y))
%o A300566 /* Code below for illustration only, not guaranteed to give a complete list. Half-integral values give the additional term 31505922 for b = 63/2. Third-integral values give the additional solution z = 342732 for b = 26/3. */
%o A300566 S=[]; N=1e5; forstep(b=1,9,1/3, forstep(a=1,N,1/3, issquare(b^10+a^4<<2,&r)&& !frac(z=b^5/2+r/2)&& !print1(z",")&&S=setunion(S,[z])); print1([b])); S
%Y A300566 Cf. A300564 (z^4 = x^2 + y^3) and A242183, A300565 (z^5 = x^3 + y^4), A302174.
%Y A300566 Cf. A100294: numbers of the form a^5 + b^4.
%Y A300566 See A303266 for the y-values.
%K A300566 nonn,more,hard,changed
%O A300566 1,1
%A A300566 _M. F. Hasler_, Apr 16 2018
%E A300566 a(4)-a(6),a(8),a(10)-a(12) from _Jacques Tramu_ and a(7),a(9),a(13)-a(14) from _M. F. Hasler_ confirmed and added by _Max Alekseyev_, Apr 04 2026
%E A300566 a(15) from _Max Alekseyev_, Apr 09 2026
